rupt the casting of the said mob 80% of the time. This leads to getting your MT getting nuked less thus requiring the cleric to heal less. Also the stun is a form of damage migitation (if a mob is stunned for even 3 secs that's 1 round less damage). Say if a mob quads for 400 and getting stunned for 3 secs means it saves your cleric having to heal about 1600 points of damage. The pet alternates between stunning and rooted (which is useful against mob that flees).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Problem is, mobs that are 55+ cannot be stunned. You'll still get the message saying they are, but they aren't actually stunned. Used to be they wouldn't be stunned, but spells could still be interrupted, but seems they changed that awhile ago. So once your fighting 55+ mobs, stuns aren't doing anything at all (and at level 65, you have to fight 55+ mobs for xp).<br>
<br>
This is an issue with higher end air pets as well. One of the air pets strengths is it's stun spell. This spell is little more than a weak DD against many xp mobs you'll be fighting post 60.<br>
<br>
The idea of a casting pet was interesting, would have gotten around the issue with bane-only mobs. Just a shame poor implementation has kept them from actually being useful.<br>
<br>
Chain-stunning pets are great in Seb, but at the level you get Child of Ro, you won't be hunting there anymore. You'll most likely be fighting mobs that cannot be stunned, which makes this pet basiclly worthless.<br>
<br>
Kinelaria<br>
Taeru<br>
